answers.body_markdown:
Remove the return statements from switch cases, 
Once you return inside the switch case, the place where you are updating `this.tip[i] = TIPz;` is never executed and becomes unreachable.

&gt; **[The return statement][1]** ends function execution and specifies a value to be returned to the function caller. 
&gt; 
&gt; When a return statement is used in a function body, the execution of
&gt; the function is stopped. If specified, a given value is returned to
&gt; the function caller.


&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var john = {
      Billamounts: [124, 48, 268, 180, 42],
      tip: [],
      TipCalc: function() {
        for (var i = 0; i &lt; this.Billamounts.length; i++) {
          var TIPz;
          var bill = this.Billamounts[i];

          switch (true) {
            case (bill &lt; 50):
              TIPz = this.Billamounts[i] * (20 / 100);
              break;

            case ((bill &gt;= 50) &amp;&amp; (bill &lt;= 200)):
              TIPz = this.Billamounts[i] * (15 / 100);
              break;

            case (bill &gt; 200):
              TIPz = this.Billamounts[i] * (10 / 100);
              break;

          }
          this.tip.push(TIPz);
        }
      }
    }

    john.TipCalc();
    console.log(john.tip);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/return

`return` will exit the function and return param . So, return after your function need finished.

when you want to left `switch case` used `break`.

Usually,  `if else` is handle such as `boolean logic` and `switch` is decide which case is equal the param . 
